with Long Claw Extractor.

and Cross-bolt Recoil Lug
Magazine Capacity: 5, with Controlled Round Feeding.

clean sight picture.
Stock Material: Oil-resistant Teak Wood
Over-All Length: 42.7” The M48 rifle represents the peak developement of the K98
Mauser style infantry rifle. It’s superior design incorporated more refinements
and it was constructed of superior materials, not having
been subjected to material shortages like the rifles built in Germany.Some people may be getting the mistaken impression that these rifles were manufactured by Germans during the occupation. That is not the case. These rifles were manufactured with German and FN technology in Serbia after the people had driven the Germans out of Yugoslavia.
This is an important distinction, because that is one of the reasons why the Model 48 is recognized as an excellent example of the Mauser 98 Karbine type military rifle. The factory in Serbia was not bombed, like the German factories during the war. The factory in Serbia had a good supply of raw materials. And the Model 48 was produced by free people, instead of forced labor. All of which resulted in an excellent rifle in its own right, as well as an interesting piece of history.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Legion Saiga AK-47 (NOT Century) w/ Magpul and extras
postcontent:
Please note: this isn't one of the cheap Century WASR's, but I'm asking less than most people and stores are asking for one.  It's made in the Izmash factory, but is considered a step above standard AK and Saiga rifles that come out of there (Legion is a branch of the Izzy Arsenal, and they select their rifles by accuracy).  It was imported by Mercury-Hermes.

This is a Saiga with pistol grip with battery compartment, collapsible stock, and sling studs. It's been modified to accept standard AK-47 mags and has a bullet guide installed.  Also had the hand guards ported to help keep them cool when firing a lot.  Please note that it is NOT a "converted" Saiga - the only conversion is to accept the AK mags.  This can be switched back to the standard European-style Saiga stock and handguards (stock and handguards run about $40 online) if you don't want that "assault rifle" look, or live in an area that won't allow them to be used for hunting.

The rifle has some wear in the usual spots (mag release, side mount, safety lever, etc), but works flawlessly.

It comes with a soft "tactical" case with outside pockets for mags, etc., 2 brand new in package Magpul AK pmags, and 60 rounds of ammo.

I won't travel very far right now.  My wife just had a baby so I have to stay close to home.  If you're local you should be willing to come to Brookfield; if you're coming from up north I'm willing to meet up at Gun World or Cabela's in Richfield.  If you're from Madison area, I'll travel out to Johnson Creek to meet.
